SIMPLE: wretched
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Wretched
<hw>Wretch"ed</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Very miserable; sunk
in, or accompanied by, deep affliction or distress, as from want,
anxiety, or grief; calamitous; woeful; very afflicting.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧To
what <xex>wretched</xex> state reserved!⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O cruel! Death! to those you are more kind⟦br⟧
Than to the <qex>wretched</qex> mortals left behind.</q>
<rj><qau>Waller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- <q>The <qex>wretched</qex> refuse of your teeming shore . . .
</q> -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Worthless; paltry; very poor or mean; miserable;
<as>as, a <ex>wretched</ex> poem; a <ex>wretched</ex>
cabin</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Hatefully contemptible; despicable; wicked.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Wretched</xex> ungratefulness.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Sir P. Sidney.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nero reigned after this Claudius, of all men
<qex>wretchedest</qex>, ready to all manner [of] vices.</q>
<rj><qau>Capgrave.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wretchedly</ent>⟦br⟧
